#week-title("Two", "Comparing Plant Ash and Mineral Salt")

=== Core Teaching

The Initiate who has made a genuine Plant Stone or cohobated plant spagyric now
stands at the border between the vegetable and mineral kingdoms. This week makes
that border visible by placing a plant ash (already familiar from Year One) and
the mineral salt of tartar (produced in Week 1) side by side for direct
comparison.

The comparison operates on two levels simultaneously: the sensory-analytical
level of the laboratory, and the philosophical level of the alchemical theory.

*Laboratory comparison: what to observe.*

- *Colour:* Plant ash calcined properly tends toward white or pale grey with
  warm undertones. Salt of tartar from wood ash is typically white to yellowish-
  white. Note any differences between these and the salt of tartar from wine
  lees, which may carry a pinkish or rosy tone from residual tartrates.
- *Texture:* Plant ash tends toward fineness; salt of tartar after evaporation
  often shows visible crystal structure, granular or flaky.
- *Hygroscopic behaviour:* Both absorb atmospheric moisture, but salt of tartar
  does so far more aggressively. Plant ash, especially if calcined well, may
  be relatively stable. This difference reflects the degree to which each salt
  has been "opened" to receive the volatile.
- *Solubility:* Salt of tartar dissolves readily in distilled water; plant ash
  dissolves only partially (the soluble fraction is the true salt; the insoluble
  remainder is silica and calcium compounds).
- *Taste (with appropriate caution, minimal quantity):* Salt of tartar is
  strongly alkaline — distinctly caustic in any quantity. Plant ash has a milder
  alkaline taste, often with herbal character specific to the source plant. Do
  not taste either substance in significant quantity; a microscopic amount on
  a wetted fingertip is sufficient for a trained observation.

*Philosophical comparison: what this means.*

The Golden Chain Book II teaches that the mineral kingdom and the vegetable
kingdom share a common salt principle — both derive from the universal fixed
alkali — but the mineral salt is more deeply fixed, more fully crystallised, and
more powerful in its attraction of volatile force. The salt of tartar that
liquefies in open air is demonstrating the same principle as the Plant Stone
that cohobates the essence of its own plant: both are bodies of crystallised
universal salt attracting the volatile universal spirit. The mineral salt simply
does this at a higher degree of fixity and with a correspondingly greater
magnetic force.

=== Topics This Week

- Side-by-side laboratory comparison of plant ash and salt of tartar
- Sensory analysis: colour, texture, hygroscopicity, solubility
- The philosophical significance of the comparison: degree of fixity
- The border between vegetable and mineral as a continuous spectrum, not a wall

#inner-work[
  *The Vegetable-Mineral Border*

  Contemplate the border between kingdoms in terms of your own experience.
  What transitions in your life have felt like crossing from one "kingdom" to
  another — from one mode of being to a qualitatively different one?

  The student who has genuinely experienced the Year One work will recognise
  that the Plant Stone itself began to reveal mineral qualities as it matured.
  Was there a moment when the preparation felt less like a plant and more like
  a stone? Record what you observed.
]

